            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Background</h2>
<p>One of the most common frustrations in Meta advertising: a creative generates solid impressions and clicks but produces few conversions. These "high-volume, low-converting" creatives drain your budget until overall account ROI suffers.</p>
<p>This guide provides a step-by-step SOP to help you quickly determine during post-campaign reviews whether a creative should be scaled, optimized, or paused.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Step 1: Lock Your Review Timeframe</h2>
<h3>Standards</h3>
<p>Before diving into analysis, confirm your data window:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Time Since Launch</th>
<th>Recommended Review Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>&lt; 3 days</td>
<td>Wait for data accumulation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3-7 days</td>
<td>Check CTR and CPC trends</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>7-14 days</td>
<td>Deep-dive conversion funnel and ROAS</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>&gt; 14 days</td>
<td>Full attribution analysis with LTV evaluation</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Actions</h3>
<ul>
<li>Export campaign data for all ad set variations containing this creative</li>
<li>Confirm the attribution window used (recommend reviewing both 7-day click and 1-day click)</li>
<li>Document CPM, CTR, and CPC as baseline metrics</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Step 2: Determine If the Creative "Runs"</h2>
<h3>Quick-Reference Checklist</h3>
<p><strong>A "running" creative typically meets:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>CPM at or below category average</li>
<li>CTR at or exceeding 1% (for feed placements)</li>
<li>Daily spend reaching at least 10% of campaign budget</li>
<li>Comparable spend velocity to other variants in A/B tests</li>
</ul>
<h3>Quick Decision Rule</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>If a creative runs well with reasonable CPC but no conversions → proceed to Step 3<br />
If a creative struggles to spend → prioritize checking audience, targeting, or bidding issues</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>Step 3: Determine If the Creative "Sells"</h2>
<h3>Four-Layer Conversion Funnel Analysis</h3>
<p><strong>Layer 1: On-site Behavior</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Add-to-cart rate: Below 1% indicates the creative fails to trigger purchase intent</li>
<li>Checkout initiation rate: Large gaps between cart and checkout suggest appeal but friction on price or trust</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Layer 2: Purchase Conversion</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>CTR-to-CVR ratio: Below 0.5% for feed ads warrants attention</li>
<li>Cost per acquisition (CPA): Compare against product margin to confirm profitability</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Layer 3: ROAS Tiers</strong></p>
<p>Categorize by ROAS performance:</p>
<ul>
<li>ROAS &gt; 3x: High performer, scale up</li>
<li>ROAS 1.5x-3x: Stable performer, maintain with new creative tests</li>
<li>ROAS &lt; 1.5x: Underperforming, queue for optimization or pause</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Layer 4: Attribution Window Variance</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>If 7-day click ROAS significantly exceeds 1-day click ROAS, the creative has strong "consideration" value but weak immediate conversion</li>
<li>This is positive for long-decision products (games, subscriptions)</li>
<li>Requires careful evaluation for short-cycle e-commerce</li>
</ul>
<hr />
<h2>Step 4: Attribution Decision Matrix</h2>
<p>Combine findings into a final decision:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Runs?</th>
<th>Sells?</th>
<th>Action</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>✅ Yes</td>
<td>✅ Yes</td>
<td>Scale up, increase bid</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>✅ Yes</td>
<td>❌ No</td>
<td>Pause or reduce budget, iterate based on top-converting creatives</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>❌ No</td>
<td>✅ Yes</td>
<td>Review bidding/targeting, test with higher bids</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>❌ No</td>
<td>❌ No</td>
<td>Pause immediately, document learnings</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<hr />
<h2>Step 5: Post-Review Documentation Template</h2>
<p>Record the following after each creative review for team learning:</p>
<pre><code>Creative ID: [paste ID]
Launch Date: [date]
Review Date: [date]
Spend: [X] USD
CPM: [X] / CPC: [X] / CTR: [X]%
Conversions: [X] / CVR: [X]%
ROAS (7-day click): [X]x
Conclusion: □ High performer  □ High volume, low conversion  □ Low volume, high conversion  □ Underperformer
Next Steps: □ Scale  □ Pause  □ Iterate  □ Test new landing page
Owner: [name]
</code></pre>
<hr />
<h2>Common Pitfalls</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Obsessing over CTR without backend metrics</strong>: High CTR with poor landing page conversion often signals creative-to-landing page misalignment</li>
<li><strong>Evaluating new creatives with long attribution windows</strong>: Use 1-day click attribution for the first 3 days; 7-day data has high variance early on</li>
<li><strong>Ignoring creative fatigue</strong>: CTR typically decays after 14+ days of continuous exposure—prepare fresh variants in advance</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>"Running" and "selling" are distinct capability dimensions. Running measures traffic efficiency; selling measures conversion quality and ROI contribution. This SOP enables systematic creative reviews, replacing guesswork with data-driven decisions on which creatives deserve your budget.</p>
